Bathyzetes umbrella
is readily distinguished from the other species owing to its cephalon being shorter than the other trunk segments (as long as or longer than the other trunk segments in the other species), its abdomen extending to more than half the length of the second coxa of the fourth leg (only just exceeding tip of first coxa in the other species, owing to the more elongate coxae), and oviger article 5 longer than article 4 . Other differences, such as shorter proboscis and abdomen in relation to the trunk (also the case for
B. extenuata
), the proportionately shorter distal chelifore article, and the proportions of the palp and oviger articles (P 6 much shorter, O 6 much longer in
B. umbrella
) are summarized in
Table 1
(see also
Loman 1908
;
Calman 1938
).
